**Typical benefit**: 20-90% for multi-way joins with varying cardinalities

## Test Cases

### Positive Case 1: Star Join

```sql
SELECT *
FROM fact f
JOIN dim1 d1 ON f.dim1_id = d1.id
JOIN dim2 d2 ON f.dim2_id = d2.id
JOIN dim3 d3 ON f.dim3_id = d3.id;

-- May reorder to: (fact ⋈ small_dim) ⋈ other_dims
-- Instead of left-deep: ((fact ⋈ dim1) ⋈ dim2) ⋈ dim3
```

### Positive Case 2: Chain Join with Selectivity

```sql
SELECT * FROM t1
JOIN t2 ON t1.id = t2.t1_id
JOIN t3 ON t2.id = t3.t2_id
WHERE t3.status = 'active';  -- highly selective

-- May reorder to apply selective filter early
```

### Negative Case 1: Join Hints Present

```sql
SELECT * FROM t1
INNER HASH JOIN t2 ON t1.id = t2.id
JOIN t3 ON t2.id = t3.id;

-- Join hint prevents reordering
```

